# Trajectory Integrity System — Project Rules

## Project Identity
This is the Trajectory Integrity System (TIS) — a gentle guidance system that ensures weekly time investment supports declared long-term direction through steady, focused progress.

The product protects long-term trajectory from short-term noise. It is NOT a sprint tool, hustle engine, habit tracker, time-logging app, or productivity dashboard. It is a steady progress alignment system.

## Emotional Tone
Every UI decision must reflect: familiar, grounded, personal, calm, direct, honest.
Never: analytical, gamified, competitive, urgent, performative.
When in doubt about copy or interaction design, choose the calmer option.

## Tech Stack
- Frontend: React 18+ with TypeScript, Vite
- Styling: Tailwind CSS
- Backend: Supabase (PostgreSQL, Auth, Row Level Security)
- PWA: vite-plugin-pwa
- Routing: React Router v7
- State: React Context + useReducer for global state, useState for local
- No Redux. No Zustand. Keep state management simple.

## Code Standards
- Functional components only. No class components.
- Named exports only. No default exports.
- Use `const` arrow functions for components: `export const MyComponent = () => {}`
- Descriptive variable names with auxiliary verbs: isLoading, hasError, canSubmit
- Keep files under 200 lines. Split when a file does more than one thing.
- Co-locate related files: component, hook, types, and test in the same directory.
- All TypeScript. No `any` type. Define interfaces for all props and data.
- Use absolute imports via `@/` path alias mapped to `src/`.

## File Naming
- Components: PascalCase directories and files (`DailyLog/DailyLog.tsx`)
- Hooks: camelCase with `use` prefix (`useDailyLog.ts`)
- Types: PascalCase with `.types.ts` suffix (`Journey.types.ts`)
- Utils: camelCase (`formatTime.ts`)
- Supabase files: camelCase (`supabaseClient.ts`)

## Component Patterns
- Props interfaces defined above the component in the same file.
- Destructure props in function signature.
- Early returns for loading, error, and empty states — handle these FIRST, not last.
- Separate data fetching (hooks) from presentation (components).
- No inline styles. Use Tailwind utility classes.
- Accessibility: all interactive elements need aria labels, minimum 44px touch targets.

## Supabase Patterns
- Single Supabase client instance exported from `src/lib/supabaseClient.ts`.
- All database queries go through custom hooks in `src/hooks/`.
- Row Level Security (RLS) enabled on ALL tables. Never bypass RLS.
- Use Supabase generated types from `src/types/database.types.ts`.
- Environment variables: `VITE_SUPABASE_URL` and `VITE_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY`.

## Error Handling
- Wrap all Supabase calls in try/catch.
- Surface user-friendly error messages — never expose raw database errors.
- Use a consistent error state pattern: `{ error: string | null, isLoading: boolean }`.
- Log errors to console in development only.

## Testing
- Test critical paths only: onboarding, daily log, weekly ritual, recalibration.
- Use Vitest for unit tests, Testing Library for component tests.
- Test file lives next to the file it tests: `DailyLog.test.tsx`.
